solar_foam_animation.py is a stand‑alone Python program that

loads the baseline foam grid that you created with baseline_foam_map.py,
places the Sun, planets, dwarf planets and a few large moons on that grid using a simple Keplerian ephemeris (good enough for a visual sandbox – you can later swap in a high‑precision SPICE kernel if you wish),
computes the foam‑distortion field that each body generates at every time‑step, using the equations that appear in Master Equation Reference.docx (gravity‑sourced foam, EM‑radiation pressure, strain → warp‑velocity, etc.),
writes the result out as a series of VTK Structured‑Grid files (one file per simulation‑step).VTK is natively understood by many open‑source 3‑D packages – Paraview, Blender (via the “Import‑VTK” add‑on), VisIt, three‑js (via vtk.js), etc.Each file contains:
the 3‑D foam‑distortion scalar (phi_dist) – visualised as a coloured wave,
a vector field (foam_force) that shows the local foam‑gradient force,
a small JSON side‑car that lists the positions, radii and display colour of every body for that frame.



The program is deliberately modular so you can later replace any of the physics blocks with a more sophisticated model (e.g. the full driven‑Mathieu equation of §5.7) without touching the I/O or the ephemeris code.



1️⃣  QUICK‑START GUIDE

          
            
            
          
# 1️⃣  Install the (very small) dependency set

pip install numpy pandas pyvtk tqdm

# 2️⃣  Save the script below as  solar_foam_animation.py

# 3️⃣  Make sure the baseline grid file exists (the program will

#      automatically import baseline_foam_map.FoamMap).

python solar_foam_animation.py  --duration-days 365  --dt-hours 1  --output ./foam_frames
      
--duration-days – how many days of solar‑system evolution you want to render.  
--dt-hours – simulation time‑step (1 h → 24 frames per day, good for smooth animation).  
--output – folder where the VTK files and the bodies_*.json side‑cars will be written.

Open the folder in Paraview → File → Open → select foam_*.vts.Enable the “phi_dist” colour map, add a Glyph source that reads the JSON file to display the planets (or import the JSON into Blender as an object‑instancing script).


3️⃣  HOW THE PHYSICS MAPS TO THE MASTER‑EQUATION REFERENCE



